  </div>
  <strong>Rate</strong> is comparison between quantities of different kinds. 
  It is also important to find the rate of one unit to easily 
  find the rate of other quantities (<strong>Unitary method</strong>).
  <br>
  <div class="container">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col border-right border-danger">
    <strong>Example 1</strong>
    <br>
    A car moves 180km in 3hours. What is its rate in km/h?
    <br>
    <strong>Solution</strong> 
    <br>
    It covers 180km in 3hours;
    <br>
    In 1 hour, it moves <sup>180</sup>&frasl;<sub>3</sub> = 60km
    <br>
    The rate = 60km/h
    <br>
    <strong>Example 2</strong>
    <br> 
  Stephen’s house rent is $1140 per year. What is his monthly payment rate?
  <br>
  <strong>1 year = 12 months </strong>
  <br>
  Monthly payment rate = <sup>1140</sup>&frasl;<sub>12</sub> = <strong>$95/month</strong>
  <br>
    </div>
    <div class="col">
    <strong>Example 3 </strong>
    <br>
    A man gets $120 for 5 hours’ work. What is his rate of pay per hour?
    <br>
    <strong>Solution </strong>
    In 5 hours, he gets = $120
    <br>
    In 1 hour, he gets = <sup>120</sup>&frasl;<sub>5</sub> = <b>$24</b>
    <br>
    His rate of pay = <strong>$24/hour</strong>
    </div>
  </div>
